    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-11-27T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-11-27T12:00:00-05:00" n="314"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d314">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.94/99: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Poland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Warsaw</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-11-27T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 27, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 27—3:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>137. Reliably informed Poland has not slightest intention of joining
                    German-Japanese anti-Communist front. Colonel Beck<note n="15" xml:id="d314fn15"
                        >Polish Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> remarked to me on 24th that
                    “The Polish Government’s relations with the Soviet Government are always
                    formally correct.” Poland ignores the Third International and paradoxically has
                    less fear of Communist propaganda than have many countries whose frontiers are
                    not contiguous to Russia.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
